04414nam a22005655i 9780822390725DE-B159720201125033335.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201125t20092009ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223907257 a10.1515/97808223907252doi  a(DE-B1597)554309  a(OCoLC)1224278947  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aB3199.A34bS3813 2009 7aPHI0000002bisacsh04a1932221 aSchweppenhäuser, Gerhard, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aTheodor W. Adorno :bAn Introduction /cGerhard Schweppenhäuser; Fredric Jameson, Stanley Fish. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2009] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (198 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPost-Contemporary Interventions00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface to the English Edition -- tTranslator's Preface -- t1 The Project of Renewing Childhood by Transforming One's Life -- t2 Critical Theory -- t3 Reason's Self-Criticism -- t4 Rescuing What is Beyond Hope -- t5 The Totally Socialized Society -- t6 The Goal of the Emancipated Society -- t7 The Powerless Utopia of Beauty -- t8 The Failure of Culture -- tBiographical Timeline -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aTheodor W. Adorno (1903-1969) was one of the twentieth century's most important thinkers. In light of two pivotal developments-the rise of fascism, which culminated in the Holocaust, and the standardization of popular culture as a commodity indispensable to contemporary capitalism-Adorno sought to evaluate and synthesize the essential insights of Western philosophy by revisiting the ethical and sociological arguments of his predecessors: Kant, Nietzsche, Hegel, and Marx. This book, first published in Germany in 1996, provides a succinct introduction to Adorno's challenging and far-reaching thought. Gerhard Schweppenhäuser, a leading authority on the Frankfurt School of critical theory, explains Adorno's epistemology, social and political philosophy, aesthetics, and theory of culture.After providing a brief overview of Adorno's life, Schweppenhäuser turns to the theorist's core philosophical concepts, including post-Kantian critique, determinate negation, and the primacy of the object, as well as his view of the Enlightenment as a code for world domination, his diagnosis of modern mass culture as a program of social control, and his understanding of modernist aesthetics as a challenge to conceive an alternative politics. Along the way, Schweppenhäuser illuminates the works widely considered Adorno's most important achievements: Minima Moralia, Dialectic of Enlightenment (co-authored with Horkheimer), and Negative Dialectics. Adorno wrote much of the first two of these during his years in California (1938-49), where he lived near Arnold Schoenberg and Thomas Mann, whom he assisted with the musical aesthetics at the center of Mann's novel Doctor Faustus.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Nov 2020) 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh1 aFish, Stanley, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aJameson, Fredric, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aRolleston, James08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822390725zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822390725423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822390725.jpg  a978-3-11-071183-7  DUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles